<h2><strong>How Tight Should the Brace Be?</strong></h2>
<p>You'll want to have compression, feeling of tightness in your knee when using a knee brace. It should feel comfortable and provide a level of support necessary based on your individualized needs. However, if the brace is uncomfortably tight and you're losing circulation, it's time to loosen the straps or choose a larger sized brace. Rigid braces provide more support and feel rigid, while compression sleeves allow for more movement but less support.Use a size chart to determine which <span style="text-decoration: underline; color: #cc132c;"> <strong> <a href="http://www.mcdavidusa.com/knee-sleeve-w-anterior-patch-open-patella/?utm_source=Blog&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=How%20to%20choose%20the%20right%20knee%20brace&amp;utm_content=post" style="color: #cc132c; text-decoration: underline;">flexible knee sleeve</a> </strong> </span> to choose based on the circumference (distance around) your knee below the center of the knee cap.</p>
<br>
<h2><strong>Which Brace to Choose?</strong></h2>
<p>The right <span style="text-decoration: underline; color: #cc132c;"> <strong> <a href="https://familydoctor.org/knee-bracing-what-works/?utm_source=Blog&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=How%20to%20choose%20the%20right%20knee%20brace&amp;utm_content=post" style="color: #cc132c; text-decoration: underline;">knee brace for you</a> </strong> </span> depends on the level of support needed and/or what your doctor recommends. This decision is based on whether or not you're recovering from surgery, the type of injury you have, and how much movement your knee should be getting.</p>
